Daughters
Before the Qing court moved to Beijing in 1644, Manchu women used to have personal names, but after 1644 these names &quot;disappear from the genealogical and archival records.&quot;251 Only after their betrothal were imperial daughters given a title and rank, by which they then became known.252 Although five of the Shunzhi Emperor's six daughters died in infancy or childhood, they all appear in the Aisin Gioro genealogy.253

1st daughter (1652&lt;U+2013&gt;1653).254 Born to Consort Chen &lt;U+9673&gt;.255
2nd daughter (1654&lt;U+2013&gt;1685): second-rank Princess (M.: ho&lt;U+0161&gt;oi gungju) Gongyi Chang (Ch.: heshuo Gongyi Chang gongzhu &lt;U+548C&gt;&lt;U+78A9&gt;&lt;U+606D&gt;&lt;U+61FF&gt;&lt;U+9577&gt;&lt;U+516C&gt;&lt;U+4E3B&gt;).256 Born to Consort Yang &lt;U+694A&gt;.257 Married in 1667 to Manchu Nerdu (&lt;U+8A25&gt;&lt;U+723E&gt;&lt;U+675C&gt;; d. 1676), of the Guwalgiya clan.258
3rd daughter (1654&lt;U+2013&gt;1658).259 Born to Consort Ba &lt;U+5DF4&gt;.260
4th daughter (1655&lt;U+2013&gt;1662).261 Born to Consort Usu &lt;U+70CF&gt;&lt;U+8607&gt;.262
